{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474785","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474785"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:24:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12399"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12399"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.73,0.01,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4907"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46009"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4907"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12399"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30936"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1086"},{"type":"tags","id":"1845"},{"type":"tags","id":"1925"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46009","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/46009"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-year-old boy presents to his General Practice clinic with his mother with a two-month history of generalised swelling, particularly around his ankles. His mother has also noticed frothy urine and that he has gained about 4 kg in weight. He has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 13/min, and temperature 38.6\u00b0C. There is mild bilateral pitting oedema on his lower extremities and some periorbital oedema. His chest is clear with no added sounds. A 24-hour urine protein measurement shows 4 g of protein.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Furosemide","Prednisolone","Rituximab","Cyclosporin","Lisinopril"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with signs and symptoms of nephrotic syndrome, which is confirmed by the presence of 4 g protein in a 24-hour urine sample (normal \u003C3.5 g). \u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E, a corticosteroid, is the first-line treatment option for patients with nephrotic syndrome. The exact mechanism of action is not fully understood, but it is believed that corticosteroids regulate nuclear gene expression via the cytosolic glucocorticoid receptor, activating genes for anti-inflammatory cytokines and suppressing genes for pro-inflammatory cytokines.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of fever (38.6\u00b0C) in this child with nephrotic syndrome is concerning, as it may indicate an underlying infection. Children with nephrotic syndrome are at increased risk of infections due to urinary losses of immunoglobulins and the immunosuppressive effects of corticosteroid treatment. Therefore, while initiating prednisolone therapy, it is crucial to promptly evaluate and treat any potential infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFurosemide\u003C/strong\u003E, a diuretic, can help in removing oedematous fluid, especially when it is causing symptoms. However, it does not resolve the underlying pathology and is not used as a first-line treatment option for nephrotic syndrome. In cases of severe or symptomatic oedema, furosemide might be considered as an initial treatment, but that is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERituximab\u003C/strong\u003E, an anti-B cell antibody, can be used for the treatment of steroid-dependent or frequently relapsing nephrotic syndrome. However, it is not a first-line drug, and a trial of steroids should be given initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECyclosporin\u003C/strong\u003E, a calcineurin inhibitor, is used in patients with steroid-dependent or frequently relapsing nephrotic syndrome. In cases of steroid-resistant nephrotic syndrome, calcineurin inhibitors are the first-line choice, and other agents are employed if there is no response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELisinopril\u003C/strong\u003E, an ACE inhibitor, is used in patients with secondary nephrotic syndrome, such as that secondary to diabetic nephropathy. By reducing proteinuria, these drugs lead to reduced intraglomerular pressure, causing a reduction in systemic blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Corticosteroids are the first-line treatment option for nephrotic syndrome.","Fever in a child with nephrotic syndrome may indicate an underlying infection, which requires prompt evaluation and treatment."],"references":["Tapia C, Bashir K. Nephrotic Syndrome. [Updated 2022 Jun 5]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-.","Hahn D, Hodson EM, Willis NS, Craig JC. Corticosteroid therapy for nephrotic syndrome in children. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2015 Mar 18;2015(3):CD001533. doi: 10.1002/14651858.CD001533.pub5. PMID: 25785660; PMCID: PMC7025788."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30936"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12399"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"30936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/30936"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-05-26T18:25:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T10:28:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4907"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"46009"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"att